description.text: a moana 2d plaque

Please Note:

  • This is a work in progress and may or may not be missing features required by some.
  • My print (as shown in photos) were printed mirrored along the X-axis so i had to install
    them upside down, but they still work the same way.
  • Please read info and notices below.

Info:
These parts make up an improved version of the stock HICTOP XZ-Axis. This is like many of the other XZ axis designs out there with a different take on how to adjust X-Axis belt tightness. This design does away with the small 8mm fanged bearings used as the idler on the right side in favor of a 20t 5mm bore toothless idler pulley designed for 6mm wide GT2 belts. The larger diameter of the idler decreases X-Axis friction substantially when the belt is tight, while at the same time keeps the belt parallel with it self.

Notices:

  • If you use a Z-Axis endstop that mounts to a XZ-axis part, then comment below and I may add a version that accommodates that.
  • You will need a new X-Axis belt as this method of X-Axis belt adjustment requires a much longer belt than the stock printer as well as many other designs.

Required Parts:
Stock parts: X Stepper, x4 LM8UU bearings (or equivalent), X Rods, Z Rods, etc...
A HICTOP style Prusa i3 design with 8mm Lead-screws and their respective flange nuts.
x10 M3 x10 screws (two of these can be longer)
x10 M3 nuts
x1 M5 x25 bolt (or similar length)
x1 M5 nylon insert nut (regular nut may work)
x1 20T 5mm bore toothless idler pulley for 6mm wide GT2 belts
Probably a longer GT2 x-axis belt.

This is a remix of ChaosCoreTech's Baby Dory: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1704751.

I splitted it in two halves to avoid printing it with supports (someone asked in the comments of original Baby Dory's comment section, which motivated me to do it myself).

I printed at 60% of the provided STL file which is ChaosCoreTech's original file size.

To split it, I used Blender and then had to lower the number of faces to be able to export it as a 3DS file to then import it in Sketchup and finally exporting it to STL (I know, there must be a more simple way, feel free to add suggestions in comments :) ) !

Notes:

As Dory is splitted in two parts lying on the flank, no supports are needed.
As there is the two parts printed at the same time, there is no problem with too hot filament on the fins.
I printed at 60% of the provided STL file which is ChaosCoreTech's original file size.
I suggest to not print it smaller than that as fins are really fragile at 60%.
It took me 1h40 and 14g PLA to print it with an infill of 17% and 0.15 mm resolution.

Paint job

It took a little bit of sanding to obtain a smooth surface.
I then used :

  • mastic spray (used for car bodywork) to smooth it more.
  • universal white spray primer (two layers).
  • acrylic paint applied with small paintbrushes (I don't have an airbrush, but ChaosCoreTech's wife paint job made me want to buy one !), two or three layers,
  • spray varnish, three layers.

description.text:
This is a power supply box for a 12v 5A PSU. I will be using this to power LED strips on my 3D Printer. The back features a cutout for 120/240v IEC320 C14 power cable inlet(computer cable). Also a power switch is integrated. The front features 6 DC Power Jacks. The top features ventilation slots.

The bottom has 2 holes for mounting this exact PSU with m3 x 5mm screws. I don't know if it will work on other PSUs from other vendors. The fit is tight though. It could pretty much just sit in there by friction. Another option would be double sided tape or hot glue along the top edge. The back panel snaps in place when I printed it. Some light sanding, scraping might be needed to make it fit just right. If it's too loose, you can hot glue it so it's not permanent.

In the future, I may incorporate a magnet securing system for the back panel. Designed in Fusion 360. I've attached the design file in case you want to tinker with it. It's probably sloppy as I'm new to 360 and modeling in general, but meh. The power inlet is offset simply cause I'm lazy. Originally I had the DC jacks on the same side as the power inlet, but I wanted room for expansion. So, I moved them to the front so I could have 6 instead of 4. I didn't feel like re-sketching and modeling the back, so I left it offset.

title: Wanhao i3 V2 Ultimate Glass Bed Holder

description.text:
I got tired of trying the other glass bed holders that encapsulate the adjustment screws. All the corner ones I tried would just flex and actually cause the glass to bend up.

This version is fully supported by design as the adjustable "knobs" used to hold the glass clamp the aluminum table in between. Each "knob" has a 30 degree angle around the edge so that it will naturally force the glass down to the bed. One thing to note is I do not use anything under the glass like silicon pads, so each knob is only 3.5mm thick to be used on 3mm glass. If you use anything under the glass you will have to create your own "knobs".

I used a wall thickness of 6 so that the entire area between the bolt hole and outer edge is solid. A tiny bit of sanding was required where the two braces mate together. When placing the glass on the aluminum bed you will probably notice that the glass will have a crown on one side. Place the crowned side down so the corners are the points that are raised off the bed as the corners will get pushed down by the "knobs"....then you will have a nice flat bed.

It is best to use button head socket head cap screws so that the heads of the bolts clear any fan shroud easily. I got mine from Bolt Depot and you will need 8 bolts, washers and nuts.

You will need to remove the x belt tensioner spring, as it will hit the inside of this part. This is designed to be used with Catan tile pieces for 2 cylindrical magnets.
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2093075
The newer 3 mm cylindrical magnets I bought were a slightly tighter squeeze. I could no longer push them easily by hand, so I decided to create this object to help me put the magnets in the tile bases. 35mm M3 bolts are used to torque the magnets into place with M3 nuts in slots. A series of magnets can be loaded in through the large slot in the top. The tile is placed in the center and all 4 screws are tightened down. This also helps make sure you get the polarity right in all cases. Assembly instructions:

  1. print both halves of the light mount
  2. cut a length of 16 ga. wire slightly shorter than the overall length of the mount.
  3. using pliers or a clamp press the wire into one of the long hinges on the mount.
  4. again, press the other half onto the exposed half of the wire.
  5. cut a short length of wire to insert into the bottom locking hinge.
  6. bend the remainder, and trim so it doesn't stick far from the mount.
  7. install the keymod nuts by pressing the nuts into the large oblong holes, then insert the screws into the other side and tighten until they have grip on the nuts.

description.text: Dual binding post dish for speaker. Typically this would be used to connect two different amplifiers to one speaker for bi-amped operation. I've included a link to the binding posts I use and modeled this part to fit. Print it face down (will be a pain to pop off the bed) and then hit it with some satin black spray paint to make it look super professional when done. These turned out pretty awesome and in the application I used them for they look like the aluminum single binding post dishes they replaced! Awesome! :)

50%

Notes:

I needed a dual binding post dish to modify an existing speaker to be bi-amped. I couldn't find anything to fit the bill, so modeled this to fit my needs. It is designed to fit into an appropriately shaped 4.5mm recess in the back of the speaker with a centered 3" (76mm) hole. I've attached a picture of the unfinished rear panel of the speaker for reference. You don't have to do the recess for the dish, just drill a 3" hole and screw this onto the back of your speaker and you should be all set.

Specific binding posts used are from Parts Express (part number 091-1245).
https://www.parts-express.com/dayton-audio-bpa-38g-hd-binding-post-pair-gold--091-1245

I made it thick with extra bracing on the back to make sure its strong and will stand the test of time. There are two files with two different thicknesses to the rear stiffening flange (the ~3" circle feature). Now that I've made a few of these I don't think its necessary to have this feature printed so tall, so I cut it down and uploaded both files here so you can print your preference.

The print you see in the pictures was done on medium settings with black PLA. I printed it face down and then finished it off with satin black spray paint on the face of the part to give it a professional look. As long as your speakers aren't located outdoors then PLA with a light coat of spray paint should stand the test of time just fine, but of course choose the best filament for your application.

H is for High, L is for Low (incase that wasn't obvious) and indicates that the adjacent binding posts are connected to the high frequency section or low frequency section in the speakers.

Let me know if you have any questions. Happy Making!
-erik

You know your printer, you can make some test prints and try it out.

I uploaded the Skeckup models, so you can change their fit as well.
Also you can open the Skeckup models and delete the killers panel designs and replace them with your own art, its very modular.

More Info:
If you are going to use just frame you might want to run some test prints. When I printed all the parts, the fit was fine on their own, but when it came time to put in the last panel all the tolerance build up for bottom length of the panels made it a little too small to squeeze in place. I ended up shaving some material off to make it work.

This is also true for the side connecting interfaces, might have to shave a bit off to make them fit nice. But these tolerance are going to be based on your printer.

When it came to the top the slot to fit all the parts was not wide enough. The first few layers on my printer were way bigger then they should have been, so nothing could slide in. You can make it bigger in yourself in sketchup, or just hot glue it together anyway (what I did, but then the top wont come off).

LEDS:
Simply glue each resistor into the inner cube facing each other. Then solder one resistor to the anode of each led. (Anode is the longer leg.)
And cover the connection with heatshrink to protect from shorts. Use a wire to connect / solder the opposite end of all of the resistors together. Extend that wire out of the hole in the bottom of the case.
Connect each of the cathodes together and extend that wire out through the bottom hole in case.

Led Strip:
Simply cut the cable off giving yourself enough room to connect the red wire to the wire joining all of the LED anodes together and the black to the wire joining all the cathodes.

Then all you need to do is attach the positive and negative cables to the DC jack.
Make sure you get the polarity the correct way around and that you only use 5V.

description.text:
Simple filament guide that clips to the top of the 6mm Prusa i3 MK2 gantry. I saw some horror pictures of people's spools overspinning on free rolling spool holders then binding up on the outer part of the axle as the filament is used up. Someone said a guide helps prevent that.

So I noticed a guide prevents the spool from overspinning too much as the filament will bind against the guide instead of freely flowing out towards the front of the printer. Also, the guide keeps the filament centered on the spool preventing filament from running out on the sides and getting caught up on the axle.
